Issues.Body:
**.NET Core Version:**
master

**Have you experienced this same bug with .NET Framework?:**
probably

**Problem description:**
As noted [here in a PR](https://github.com/dotnet/winforms/pull/3476#discussion_r443216116) the constrcutor of `Cursor` taking a `Stream` is broken

```cs
public Cursor(Stream stream)
{
    if (stream == null)
    {
        throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(stream));
    }

    int length = checked((int)stream.Length);
    _cursorData = new byte[length];
    stream.Read(_cursorData, 0, length);
    LoadPicture(
        new Ole32.GPStream(new MemoryStream(_cursorData)),
        nameof(stream));
}
```

- if the stream position isn't at zero the buffer would be allocated too large (suboptimal)
- if the stream doesn't know its length this would throw even though it doesn't have to (bug)
- `Read` is allowed to read less then `length` bytes so cursor data may be incomplete (bug)

Users can work around those bugs by wrapping their stream, but really the code should do a `stream.CopyTo(MemoryStream)` to let it do the heavy lifting and be more compatible to passing in arbitrary streams.

Note the current code doesn't throw, it just over-allocates and then reads less bytes than requested, which is fine if the cursor data is still represented completely at the current position.

**Expected behavior:**
- streams which don't expose their length can still be read
- streams which provide data in chunks still can be loaded

**Minimal repro:**
provide a custom stream
